
Concept	Definition	Example
Class	Blueprint for objects	class Car { }
Object	Instance of a class	$myCar = new Car();
Encapsulation	Hides data, allows controlled access	private $balance; with getBalance()
Abstraction	Hides implementation details	abstract class Vehicle {}
Inheritance	One class inherits another	class Dog extends Animal {}
Polymorphism	Multiple behaviors using the same method	overloading and overriding
Method Overloading	Same method name, different parameters (Not in PHP)	Simulated using __call()
Method Overriding	Child class modifies parent method	class Child extends Parent {}

.then()	Handles resolved promises
.catch()	Catches rejected promises
.finally()	Runs after resolution/rejection
Promise.all()	Runs multiple promises together
Promise.race()	Returns first resolved promise
async/await	Simplifies promise handling


What are the four principles of OOP?
The four main principles of Object-Oriented Programming (OOP) are:

Abstraction hides unnecessary details and shows only important parts.
Encapsulation hides data to prevent unauthorized access.

Encapsulation – Bundling data and methods together.
Abstraction – Hiding implementation details and exposing only necessary functionality.
abstract class Animal {
    abstract public function makeSound();
}
class Dog extends Animal {
    public function makeSound() {
        return "Bark";
    }
}
Inheritance – Deriving new classes from existing ones.
Polymorphism – One interface, multiple implementations.


What is final keyword, and how does it work?
✅ Answer:
The final keyword prevents class inheritance and method overriding.

 What is an interface, and how is it different from an abstract class?
✅ Answer:
An interface defines method signatures without implementation. A class implementing an interface must define all its methods.

interface Animal {
    public function makeSound();
}
class Dog implements Animal {
    public function makeSound() {
        return "Bark";
    }
}


Function Overriding: A child class redefines a parent method.
Function Overloading: Same method name, different parameters (not supported in PHP).

class ParentClass {
    public function greet() {
        return "Hello from Parent";
    }
}
class ChildClass extends ParentClass {
    public function greet() {
        return "Hello from Child";
    }
}




Feature	Description
Objects	Define structured data with key-value pairs.
Type Alias (type)	Used to create reusable object types.
Interfaces (interface)	Defines object structures with strict rules.
Optional Properties (?)	Allows some properties to be optional.
Readonly Properties (readonly)	Prevents modification of object properties.
Extending Interfaces (extends)	Inherits properties from another interface.
Function Signatures	Defines function structures inside interfaces.
Index Signatures ([key: string])	Allows dynamic object properties.



Feature	Description
Function Annotations	Explicitly define parameter and return types.
Optional Parameters	Use ? to make a parameter optional.
Default Parameters	Assign default values to parameters.
Arrow Functions	Short syntax for functions (=>).
Rest Parameters	Accept multiple arguments (...args).
Function Overloading	Define multiple function signatures.
Void Return Type	Used when function does not return a value.
Never Return Type	Used when function never completes (throws errors).
Callbacks	Functions passed as arguments.
Function Types	Use type or interface for reusable function types.



Feature	Description
Type Annotations	Explicitly define types (string, number, boolean).
Type Inference	TypeScript detects types automatically.
Union Types	Allow multiple types (`string
Type Aliases	Create reusable custom types (`type ID = string
Objects	Define strict object structures.
Functions	Define types for parameters and return values.
Optional & Default Params	Make parameters optional (?) or set defaults.
Arrays & Tuples	Store multiple values in a structured way.
Enums	Define named constants.
any, void, never	Flexible (any), no return (void), no completion (never).
Null & Undefined	Handle optional values safely.
Type Assertions	Convert one type into another (as).
